      <body>
         <div type="edition" ana="#b1" subtype="diplomatic" xml:id="akas0001.diplomatic" corresp="#akas0001.transcription #akas0001.translation">
            <p>ΘΑΡΣΙ<lb/>ΣΗΕΟ<lb/>ΣΕΤ<lb/>Ο</p>
         </div>
         <div type="edition" ana="#b1" subtype="transcription" xml:id="akas0001.transcription" corresp="#akas0001.diplomatic #akas0001.translation">
            <p>θάρσι <lb/> Σηεο<lb/>ς <expan>
                  <abbr>ἐτ</abbr>
                  <ex>ῶν</ex>
               </expan>
               <lb/> ο'</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="akas0001.translation" corresp="#akas0001.diplomatic #akas0001.transcription">
            <p>Be of good courage, Seeos! Seventy years old.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This tombstone was originally discovered by Urman's survey team during a brief visit to the site in 1968. The inscription is complete, but there is some damage to the stone. The upper left corner is broken, and there is chipping at the right edge of line two. The name Σηεος is derived from the Hebrew עיש.</p>
         </div>
